Escape

“I had read about some people escaping North Korea, going through China with no documents, and coming to freedom in South Korea through Mongolia. I thought that would be impossible. But I also thought what should I lose someday to have a better life?”

“To cross the border I had to be at least 150 pounds to fit in a painting bucket (that would hold me in the river). I made myself gain weight by sitting under the sun and eating better food.

“I was so surprised that people could get lucky and escape North Korea.

“Anybody could be in my hands: my boss, my father, my mother, my wife, my son, and sister. Anybody could turn on me.

“All these make this impossible ever again and makes the escape so much more amazing. The escape to South Korea is so much more, not just food and water, but so much money. I love this country so much.”

Life in South Korea

“The conditions of living is very different from here and there. Before I came here, I was teaching laptop and Internet to farmers. I was having a stable life.

“When I first came to South Korea I didn’t know anything. I had to live without knowing anything or anyone in the first few weeks.

I was crying for three weeks.
